## ğŸš© What is `hexstyle`?

`hexstyle` is a tiny, dependency-free Python package that lets you print colored text in your terminal using HEX color codes â€” just like in web design. It's simple, lightweight, and supports every imaginable color with easy-to-use helper functions.

---

## ğŸš€ Installation

Install from PyPI:

```bash
pip install hexstyle
```

PyPI: [https://pypi.org/project/hexstyle/](https://pypi.org/project/hexstyle/)

---

## ğŸ§© Quick usage

```py
import hexstyle

print(hexstyle.set("#ff0000") + "Hello, world!" + hexstyle.reset())
```

`hexstyle.set(hex: str)`

* `hex`: the hex color you want to use

---

## ğŸ“š Features

* Use any HEX color to style your terminal text
* Lightweight & dependency-free â€” pure Python
* Works on most modern terminals (Windows, macOS, Linux)

---

## âš ï¸ Notes & Limitations

* ANSI color codes may not display correctly in environments that don't support truecolor (24-bit) â€” for example, some older Windows terminals or minimal Docker shells.
* Output colors may vary slightly depending on your terminal theme or emulator.
* This package only affects terminal (stdout) text â€” it wonâ€™t color text in log files or GUI applications.
* Unicode/emoji characters work fine, but truecolor accuracy may vary between fonts or shells.

---

## ğŸ§ª Examples

A short interactive example:

```py
import hexstyle

print(hexstyle.set("#ff0000") + "Hello, world!" + hexstyle.reset())
input(hexstyle.set("#00ff00") + "How are you today?: " + hexstyle.set("#0000ff"))
```

---

## ğŸ†˜ Quick Fix

* If you see weird formatting like `â†[38;2;255;0;0mHello, world!â†[0m`, try **clearing the terminal** (`cls` on Windows, `clear` on Linux/macOS) or **switching to a terminal that supports ANSI colors**.

